WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.670 --> 00:00:10.161
&gt;&gt;Male presenter: Hello, everybody. Thanks
for coming to Digital Arts@Google, the artist

00:00:10.161 --> 00:00:18.500
lecture series for the second exhibition.
Today, we have a great speaker line-up for

00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:31.510
you: Eduardo Kac, Marina Zurkow, Sandra Cordero
and our very own Andrew Senior. So, the Digital

00:00:31.510 --> 00:00:39.610
Arts@Google Exhibition Series was started
by Josh Mittlemen, when he was thinking about

00:00:39.610 --> 00:00:45.269
Google's mission, which is to organize the
world's information and make it accessible.

00:00:45.269 --> 00:00:52.150
And being here in New York City, and especially
in Chelsea, in the arts district, he thought,

00:00:52.150 --> 00:00:58.530
"Well, art is a great way to access or understand
information and so Google should be involved

00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:10.050
in art and so he found Nina Colosi and invited
her to curate a series of art shows here to

00:01:10.050 --> 00:01:19.049
further that and to also foster a collaboration
between artists and engineers. And the, and

00:01:19.049 --> 00:01:26.180
this is the third lecture series and they'll
be another one. The next show opens, let's

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:34.820
see what, Nina, remind me what. Next Thursday
is the opening for the next show here in Chelsea

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:40.909
Market. So, tonight we have first

00:01:40.909 --> 00:01:46.030
[pause]

00:01:46.030 --> 00:01:57.909
speaking first will be Eduardo Kac, a pioneer
of telecommunications art started in the pre-Web

00:01:57.909 --> 00:02:03.510
80s and then emerged in the early 90s with
his radical works combining telerobotics and

00:02:03.510 --> 00:02:09.220
living organisms. His visionary integration
of robotics, biology and networking explores

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:16.790
the fluidity of subject positions in the post-Digital
world. His work deals with the mythopoetics

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:24.069
of online experience, cultural impact of biotechnology,
conditions of memory in the digital age, distributive

00:02:24.069 --> 00:02:31.739
collective agency and the creation of life
itself. At the dawn of the 21st Century, Kac

00:02:31.739 --> 00:02:38.689
opened a new direction with contemporary art
with his transgenic art. First, the groundbreaking

00:02:38.689 --> 00:02:44.819
Genesis in 1999, which included the artists
gene that he invented and then with his fluorescent

00:02:44.819 --> 00:02:49.540
rabbit called Alba. Mr. Kac.

00:02:49.540 --> 00:02:51.409
&gt;&gt;Kac: Thank you.

00:02:51.409 --> 00:02:52.409
[applause]

00:02:52.409 --> 00:02:58.760
Thank you very much. So, in reality, and this
is an interesting coincidence, those are exactly

00:02:58.760 --> 00:03:05.110
the works I'm gonna be presenting: the work
that goes with memory, the Genesis and GFP

00:03:05.110 --> 00:03:15.709
Bunny. So, we have 20 minutes and I will then
begin in 1997, with this artwork called Time

00:03:15.709 --> 00:03:20.879
Capsule. And it's an important work in my
introductory because, for me, it represents

00:03:20.879 --> 00:03:28.860
a turning point. It's a moment in which I
begin to expand my digital work in the realm

00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:36.709
of biology. The term "bioart" I coined back
in '97 specifically to signify, to connote,

00:03:36.709 --> 00:03:45.630
this passage. And the Time Capsule has, as
referenced, these seven sepia tone photographs

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:53.500
that my grandmother brought from Poland before
'39, when she escaped the war. And it is in

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:58.739
front of the seven sepia tone photographs
that represent members of her family who did

00:03:58.739 --> 00:04:07.670
not survive the war, that I implanted a microchip
live, on television and on the Web, in front

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:15.969
of them to confront the idea of analog memory
with digital memory, because a microchip records

00:04:15.969 --> 00:04:23.050
information and in the context of the live
broadcast, one of the segments included a

00:04:23.050 --> 00:04:30.320
reading of the microchip content inside my
body, both through the live program and the

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:31.320
Webcast.

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:47.640
[Women and men speaking polish speaking on
the video ]

00:04:47.640 --> 00:05:05.760
So, the doctor who was assisting is asked
to describe what's going on and he says, almost

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:11.800
like narrating a soccer match, "Well, now
the artist is implanting a microchip and he

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:21.750
is slowly moving the needle and it's over
the skin. This was, he's narrating, cause

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:28.170
of course he was, he was afraid that he would
lose his license if he actually did the work

00:05:28.170 --> 00:05:35.130
himself. So, he told me how to do this. Not
that I have the habit of using syringes. And

00:05:35.130 --> 00:05:42.180
you see if you look behind him, you see the
seven sepia tone photographs on the wall.

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:48.520
So, this idea of confronting the changing
role of memory as everything becomes digital.

00:05:48.520 --> 00:05:54.810
Analog memories are externalized, digital
memories become internalized, with the exception,

00:05:54.810 --> 00:06:01.590
of course, that we also internalize analog
memories and, in this particular case, the

00:06:01.590 --> 00:06:08.780
digital memory is retrieved. So, I had the
scanner connected to a robotic finger and

00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:14.830
through the Web.

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:20.840
[Women and men speaking polish continues on
the video]

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:33.440
This is the third segment. So, I myself did
not know what the number was. The content

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:39.570
of the microchip is a sequence of nine digits,
which you see on the screen there. And I had

00:06:39.570 --> 00:06:44.790
bought the six-pack, not of beer, but of microchips
and just picked one out of the box at the

00:06:44.790 --> 00:06:47.120
last minute. So, I myself did not know what
the number was.

00:06:47.120 --> 00:07:03.720
[Women and men speaking polish continues on
the video]

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:11.860
So, this, in '97, creating this work in which
tissue and microchips come together because

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:20.750
tissue forms around the microchip to secure
it in position. The microchip has biocompatible

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:31.361
glass. This question of digital, the digital
and the biological started to take center

00:07:31.361 --> 00:07:39.910
stage for me and in '98, I wrote a text called
"Transgenic Art" more clearly signaling the

00:07:39.910 --> 00:07:49.310
fact that I wanted to focus on the creation
of new life forms in the context of art. And

00:07:49.310 --> 00:07:54.720
produced then, in 1999, my first transgenic
work called "Genesis."

00:07:54.720 --> 00:08:31.850
[electronic music plays]

00:08:31.850 --> 00:08:56.610
[bell chimes]

00:08:56.610 --> 00:09:04.529
So, what is going on in this work? It's easier
to understand once we look at this diagram.

00:09:04.529 --> 00:09:10.240
The starting point for me was the appropriation
of a passage from the Bible, from the book

00:09:10.240 --> 00:09:15.990
of Genesis. I don't own a Bible, so I went
online, found the King James Version, copied

00:09:15.990 --> 00:09:21.740
and pasted into Microsoft Word. And if you're
thinking James and combine that with Bill

00:09:21.740 --> 00:09:24.649
Gates, that may be enough for a conceptual
artwork.

00:09:24.649 --> 00:09:25.649
[laughter]

00:09:25.649 --> 00:09:30.899
But I'm not a conceptual artist, so I persevered
and translated that to Morse code. Straightforward

00:09:30.899 --> 00:09:36.120
Morse code, as you know, dots and dashes,
so what you see here under this arrow is a

00:09:36.120 --> 00:09:42.750
direct Morse code translation of that passage
from the Bible, which is a significant passage

00:09:42.750 --> 00:09:49.519
in the sense that this is where God gives
man total control over all life, and has been

00:09:49.519 --> 00:09:57.209
down the drain from there, as you know. So,
inside the box, you see a code that I created

00:09:57.209 --> 00:10:06.029
specifically for this work. On the left side,
you have the, what linguists call the motivated

00:10:06.029 --> 00:10:15.379
section of the code. Because C, which represents
cytosine in DNA, is round and so is the dot,

00:10:15.379 --> 00:10:22.550
so I established that analogy. And because
T is straight and so is the dash, I established

00:10:22.550 --> 00:10:29.980
that analogy. On the right, you have the arbitrary
part of the code, so space between the letters

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:37.170
became guanine and space between words became
adenine. So, how does this work? You have

00:10:37.170 --> 00:10:45.870
a direct translation, if you look at the bottom;
you have C-T-C-C-G. So, C-T-C-C is dot dash

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:54.749
dot dot space. And it goes on like that. So,
C-T-C-C, dot dash dot dot, is the letter L

00:10:54.749 --> 00:11:03.339
that you have up here from the original English
text. The result is that the sequence of 360

00:11:03.339 --> 00:11:09.870
genetic bases encodes the passage from the
Bible. So, when I'm doing this, I'm still

00:11:09.870 --> 00:11:16.769
working on the computer screen and I have
a text file. So I copied from my text file,

00:11:16.769 --> 00:11:23.230
pasted that into the email program and sent
that to a company specialized in DNA synthesis.

00:11:23.230 --> 00:11:29.380
Two weeks later, I got a FedEx package with
the DNA. And you look at the DNA and it's

00:11:29.380 --> 00:11:35.990
disembodied DNA and it becomes evident to
you that all this narrative that DNA has a

00:11:35.990 --> 00:11:41.089
central and dominant position in controlling
life, when you see DNA outside of the body

00:11:41.089 --> 00:11:44.949
it is very clear that without the body and
without the environment in which the body

00:11:44.949 --> 00:11:53.050
is located, DNA cannot do anything. So, what
I created then was the Genesis bacteria, which

00:11:53.050 --> 00:11:57.259
you see in this video. So now, if we look
at this again, it will make more sense.

00:11:57.259 --> 00:11:58.259
[electronic music plays]

00:11:58.259 --> 00:12:06.899
You come into the gallery, you see the Genesis
DNA sequence on one wall; a very large projection,

00:12:06.899 --> 00:12:11.420
live from the Petri dish, which is in the
center. What you see now, the biblical passage,

00:12:11.420 --> 00:12:17.389
which you see on the other wall. Behind you,
there is Morse. And here, the Web interface

00:12:17.389 --> 00:12:24.009
that allows you to turn on a UV light source
in the gallery; from home or in the gallery

00:12:24.009 --> 00:12:29.959
itself. And this is a short-wave UV, which
means that due to the high concentrated energy,

00:12:29.959 --> 00:12:36.769
it causes real biological mutation in the
DNA. In other words, if this work is in Tokyo,

00:12:36.769 --> 00:12:42.389
from New York you can change the word of God
in the body of the bacteria in Tokyo with

00:12:42.389 --> 00:12:50.809
just one click. So, after the work was finished,
it premiered at Ars Electronica in 1999, I

00:12:50.809 --> 00:12:57.620
took the bacteria back to the lab and read
the mutation and developed a series of works

00:12:57.620 --> 00:13:03.050
with the mutant text in English because I
used the code to read it back to English.

00:13:03.050 --> 00:13:10.720
Now, if you think about what this means, you
are encoding digital information into a living

00:13:10.720 --> 00:13:16.120
organism. You are changing that and then you
are retrieving it. That's exactly what we

00:13:16.120 --> 00:13:21.889
do with computers; input, processing and output,
except that you're doing that with a living

00:13:21.889 --> 00:13:28.920
organism in real time. So, to me, that represents
certain significant aspects of life in the

00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:36.480
21st Century in which, not only philosophically,
but materially, there is fundamentally really

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:44.899
no separation between digital and biological.
Processes can occur in similar manner in both

00:13:44.899 --> 00:13:53.059
environments, in both media, if we can say
so. But of course, when you talk about the

00:13:53.059 --> 00:13:59.740
living, when you talk about in the context
of art, creating an entirely new life form,

00:13:59.740 --> 00:14:05.800
you have to recognize that you're not dealing
with an object because the life form that

00:14:05.800 --> 00:14:13.061
you create is alive like you and I. So, it
shares the same properties of any living organism

00:14:13.061 --> 00:14:22.730
and empathy and responsibility become paramount
in this context. And a good example of that

00:14:22.730 --> 00:14:29.430
case is the second transgenic artwork that
I created called GFP Bunny. GFP Bunny is a

00:14:29.430 --> 00:14:35.250
piece in which I used GFP, green fluorescent
protein, the DNA that codes for this protein,

00:14:35.250 --> 00:14:42.600
