to keep that sense of a much warmer environment,

00:48:50.410 --> 00:48:57.460
where you've got a lot of humidity's and you
see the sun through yellow haze and the pollen

00:48:57.460 --> 00:49:05.059
just hanging in this really thick air. So,
while I was doing that, the Jason and Andrew

00:49:05.059 --> 00:49:12.039
writing the effects, which were then used
on jpegs which I took of the paintings. They

00:49:12.039 --> 00:49:17.660
wrote ten different effects, which are cycling
through randomly and the effects change every

00:49:17.660 --> 00:49:24.540
ten minutes. Four of the effects chop up the
image into hot blocks and then these patches

00:49:24.540 --> 00:49:29.920
are moved around randomly, or using a sine
wave over time. So, you can get that effect

00:49:29.920 --> 00:49:37.819
of leaves in the wind or of an ocean wave
moving over the image. Two of the effects

00:49:37.819 --> 00:49:45.519
work on the contrast in color of the image
and change it slowly over time. Three of the

00:49:45.519 --> 00:49:50.119
effects take pixels of the same color and
drop them down the canvas at a speed which

00:49:50.119 --> 00:49:54.489
is a function of their color. So, certain
colors move faster, slower and it creates

00:49:54.489 --> 00:50:01.369
this effect of the image melting. And there's
one colorful effect where it starts out black

00:50:01.369 --> 00:50:07.289
and then the image fills in based on the color.
Like, different colors have different starting

00:50:07.289 --> 00:50:13.940
points and then when the image is completely
