&gt;&gt;Marina: This is an unexpected prop, this
mic, so I'm gonna juggle my text. I'm gonna

00:52:57.160 --> 00:53:04.470
try to really stick to this text so I don't
start blathering. So, last year I completed

00:53:04.470 --> 00:53:12.299
a body of 11 works that fall under this title,
"Crossing the Waters." The works were made

00:53:12.299 --> 00:53:17.980
between 2006 and 2009 and the pieces thematically
address climate change. And in each of these

00:53:17.980 --> 00:53:24.140
works, I took a fairly different approach
to the material, somewhere between moving

00:53:24.140 --> 00:53:31.770
paintings and psychological narrative. So,
a few things about this series. The works

00:53:31.770 --> 00:53:37.809
are all very long, slow loops and they are
unconventionally formatted for moving images,

00:53:37.809 --> 00:53:43.020
often displayed on custom-built multi-monitor
units. Many of them are hung on the wall.

00:53:43.020 --> 00:53:53.049
They have plug and play custom computing parts
and so on. The intention of the work is to

00:53:53.049 --> 00:53:58.739
create these pieces that you would end up
living with. They're not linear pieces, they're

00:53:58.739 --> 00:54:07.299
meant to be seen over, anywhere from, some
pieces run 9 to 20 minutes, or had been running

00:54:07.299 --> 00:54:15.970
9 to 20 minutes. And here's just another example
of some smaller works from Bryce Wolkowitz

00:54:15.970 --> 00:54:22.220
Gallery. Often, the pieces are designed modularly,
so I've reformatted them. In this case, they've

00:54:22.220 --> 00:54:30.920
been scaled up installation context in a institution.
The same piece, here, you can see in Croatia

00:54:30.920 --> 00:54:35.920
in a gallery called "Grey Area" and this was
a, this is a gallery that only exists in this

00:54:35.920 --> 00:54:44.880
villa doorway and is meant to be seen from
boats passing by. This is the original format

00:54:44.880 --> 00:54:49.380
for the pieces out in the lobby, Slurb, and
it was commissioned by the city of Tampa for

00:54:49.380 --> 00:54:54.940
an outdoor Biennial festival called Lights
on Tampa and exhibited there in 2009. So,

00:54:54.940 --> 00:54:56.380
I thought, I'm not gonna show the piece because
obviously, it's out there and I hope that

00:54:56.380 --> 00:54:59.710
you'll have a chance to see it and listen
to the soundtrack, which you can only hear

00:54:59.710 --> 00:55:05.989
through the headphones out there, but the
soundtrack is pretty key to the piece. It's

00:55:05.989 --> 00:55:12.969
an 18 minute loop and a seamless 18 minute
loop. So, I thought I'd use the piece though,

00:55:12.969 --> 00:55:18.039
to describe a process of constructing the
work that I make and use Slurb as a model

00:55:18.039 --> 00:55:26.450
to demonstrate that. First of all, almost
all of the projects in this series are rotoscoped

00:55:26.450 --> 00:55:30.910
and rotoscoping is an animation technique
where you draw directly on top of video material,

00:55:30.910 --> 00:55:39.079
frame by frame. In my case, the work is completely
hand done. And the second thing I wanna say

00:55:39.079 --> 00:55:47.259
is that, despite the fact that the works look
like extremely unified pictures, they are

00:55:47.259 --> 00:55:53.140
actually a collage, cobbled together from
really disparate sources. Many of the works

00:55:53.140 --> 00:55:57.390
have a futuristic, or fantastic, tone to them,
but all of the source material for the rotoscoping

00:55:57.390 --> 00:56:05.319
was found on the Internet, a space that I'd
call in itself an inter-dependent ecosystem,

00:56:05.319 --> 00:56:10.529
and a space in which you find both competing
and complementary mean pools. All the footage

00:56:10.529 --> 00:56:14.200
I use is real, in other words, and it might
resonate as something you've saw somewhere

00:56:14.200 --> 00:56:19.210
before, from new sites, from Google searches,
YouTube and so on. The third thing is that

00:56:19.210 --> 00:56:24.489
nearly all of the elements in these works
are composed as loops. Because I work alone

00:56:24.489 --> 00:56:28.469
most of the time, and hand drawn animation
is labor intensive, using looped character

00:56:28.469 --> 00:56:34.539
behavior is very economical and efficient.
But these loops also have a really distinct

00:56:34.539 --> 00:56:41.960
stutter to them. They're very imperfect and
that adds or breaks the seamless rendered

00:56:41.960 --> 00:56:53.569
space that these pieces seems to exude and
create a kind of a brokenness. Finally, I

00:56:53.569 --> 00:56:58.059
look at these works as ambient moving paintings,
more of a narrative cartoons. And they're

00:56:58.059 --> 00:57:01.999
reminiscent of Asian scroll paintings in both
their formats and the way that the landscape

00:57:01.999 --> 00:57:07.940
is moved across the screen. What you're looking
at here is almost half of the story board

00:57:07.940 --> 00:57:14.509
for Slurb, and the 18 minute length of the
piece was determined by just a simple empirical

00:57:14.509 --> 00:57:20.019
process of seeing how long it would take to,
in a generous fashion, move this story board

00:57:20.019 --> 00:57:28.519
across the picture plane. Tampa is the site
that you see in Slurb that's half submerged.

00:57:28.519 --> 00:57:34.859
And the piece itself really looked at the
Gulf of Mexico's changing ecology, while speculating

00:57:34.859 --> 00:57:39.410
on the reality of this present day return
to a primordial sea, and what that kind of

00:57:39.410 --> 00:57:45.519
a return to an older, more primitive form
of sea, what might mean if you mixed together

00:57:45.519 --> 00:57:52.979
all of these new, speculative societies. Tampa
and the entire Gulf coast, including New Orleans,

00:57:52.979 --> 00:57:58.109
is at risk for flooding of the Gulf. It occurs
during hurricane season and the volume of

00:57:58.109 --> 00:58:02.630
these conditions is worsening from climate
change. For Lights on Tampa, I wanted to make

00:58:02.630 --> 00:58:06.950
a piece that addressed this and to create
a confluence of facts and speculations that

00:58:06.950 --> 00:58:12.809
were specific to the Gulf coast, but also
global in scope. The Gulf and the Southern

00:58:12.809 --> 00:58:17.769
Atlantic Coast used to have a healthy shrimp
fishing industry, but pollutants, agricultural

00:58:17.769 --> 00:58:23.749
run-off, over-fishing, and ocean warming,
have worldwide altered the oceans' chemical

00:58:23.749 --> 00:58:28.719
balance, rendering it acid and deprived of
oxygen. The result isn't only a significant

00:58:28.719 --> 00:58:35.049
decrease in diversity, but also a phenomenon
referred to as "the rise of slime." Slime

00:58:35.049 --> 00:58:40.640
being toxic algae, jellyfish, and other more
primitive forms of sea life. And these are

00:58:40.640 --> 00:58:47.809
forms that survive really well in the aforementioned
conditions of an epoxic ocean. So, these trawling

00:58:47.809 --> 00:58:53.130
boats used to be fitted for shrimp catches
and they've now been reconfigured to catch

00:58:53.130 --> 00:59:00.910
jellyfish for the Asian market, where they're
considered a delicacy. To explore this story

00:59:00.910 --> 00:59:06.150
of a transformed ecology, I wanted to transpose
class and cultural concerns and ask questions

00:59:06.150 --> 00:59:10.970
about who and how might thrive in these new
conditions. I started to research my cast

00:59:10.970 --> 00:59:18.270
of characters, looking for ways to soften
this relatively unpleasant scenario. I wanted

00:59:18.270 --> 00:59:23.140
to make something that had the feeling J.J.
Grandville's 19th Century satirical illustrations,

00:59:23.140 --> 00:59:33.339
creating hybrid creatures and car wrecked
mermaids and a macabre Steven King chorus

00:59:33.339 --> 00:59:38.809
that had some traces of ethnographic portraiture
and that also mined a rich history of traditionally

00:59:38.809 --> 00:59:48.720
aquatic and contemporary water-based lifestyles.
So, I became interested in portraying contemporary

00:59:48.720 --> 00:59:51.901
people accustomed to living on the water,
like the members of the Intha tribe that you

00:59:51.901 --> 01:00:00.460
see in these images. They live in Myanmar
and they live in a, not only Myanmar, there's

01:00:00.460 --> 01:00:06.450
other similar aquatic communities in Cambodia
and Vietnam, but many of them now, the lakes

01:00:06.450 --> 01:00:10.729
that they've lived on for hundreds of years
in this way and they live in houseboats and

01:00:10.729 --> 01:00:14.799
they farm hydroponically, they're, it's become
quite unsustainable cause their waterways

01:00:14.799 --> 01:00:20.630
have also become polluted by some of the same
things that I described are happening in the

01:00:20.630 --> 01:00:24.980
oceans. So, this is, for instance, a hydroponic
raft-based hydroponic farm system from this

01:00:24.980 --> 01:00:32.599
community. I was also really interested in
the optimistic design of these amphibious

01:00:32.599 --> 01:00:37.660
houses. These are being implemented in the
Netherlands and also I was really interested

01:00:37.660 --> 01:00:42.079
in this tailgate party from hell scenario.
So you can get a sense of all of that in the

01:00:42.079 --> 01:00:47.540
piece, I think. And I think this is a picture
from Morpeth, England, from the floods from

01:00:47.540 --> 01:00:52.230
two years ago. This was from a very, very
small river, very heavy rains and utterly

01:00:52.230 --> 01:00:57.010
shocked the community. They've never really
experienced anything like this. So, this is

01:00:57.010 --> 01:01:06.280
a fairly, it's a reality. It's not that far
to speculate. Finally, with Slurb, I wanted

01:01:06.280 --> 01:01:11.279
to make a travel narrative, one that unfolded
like a Chinese scroll and circled around continuously

01:01:11.279 --> 01:01:15.829
like a carousel, one that would take you from
the city of Tampa and follow its landmarks

01:01:15.829 --> 01:01:21.489
out past the broken highways and into the
suburbs and then back around again. This is

01:01:21.489 --> 01:01:30.969
actually one of the first 11 centuries, 12
century scroll from Japan, animal scroll.

01:01:30.969 --> 01:01:36.920
This is also very long. This is the site of
the projection for Slurb. Across the plaza

01:01:36.920 --> 01:01:42.170
from Tampa's ice hockey stadium was the parking
lot. Well, here. This is the parking lot that's

01:01:42.170 --> 01:01:47.069
across from this building on the right and
fortunately, during the week that the piece

01:01:47.069 --> 01:01:52.079
was projected, the circus was in town and
so, every evening at dusk, when the projector

01:01:52.079 --> 01:01:57.279
would fire up, coincidentally, the elephants
